$CATEGORY: CIT/M1/week-2/2.1-what-makes-a-good-specification-testable-bounded-observable

::q1:: In this topic, a "specification" for an AI tool is best described as which of the following? {
~A formal legal contract signed by both parties before any AI project begins, to protect everyone involved if the output turns out to be wrong#No — a specification in this context is a clear written task description you write yourself before giving an instruction, not a legal document between parties.
~A list of the AI tool's technical features, version details, and known limitations, kept on file for reference whenever you encounter unexpected results#No — a specification describes what you want the AI to do on a specific task, not a record of what the tool itself is capable of doing.
=A written description of a task detailed enough for the AI to carry it out without guessing what you meant, in what format, or how to judge success#Correct — a specification replaces guesswork with precision by stating exactly what to do, in what format, and how to judge whether the output is correct.
~A rough note jotted down to remind yourself what to ask the AI, which you can refine and expand as you go and the conversation develops#No — a rough note still leaves gaps that force the AI to guess what you meant; a specification closes every gap before the instruction is sent.
#### Tests the core definition of a specification (corpus §5.1).
}

::q2:: A student gives an AI the instruction\: "Write a lesson plan." The AI produces a plan for the wrong age group because the student never stated who the audience was. Which property was most clearly missing? {
=Actionable — the specification omitted the audience, so the AI had to guess a critical detail before it could begin working#Correct — an actionable specification answers every question the AI would need before it starts, including who the audience is, so it does not fill gaps with assumptions.
~Bounded — the topic scope was far too wide, so the AI covered far more content areas and subtopics than the student had in mind#No — the problem was not how much content was covered but that a critical piece of context — the audience — was absent when the AI started.
~Observable — the lesson plan was not a concrete output the student could actually read, review, or hand to someone else#No — a lesson plan is a document the student can read and review; the output was observable. The gap lay in missing context, not the output format.
~Testable — the student had no measurable success criterion to check the finished plan against once it had been delivered#No — testability is about checking the output against a standard after the fact; the real gap here was a missing fact needed before work could even begin.
#### Tests understanding of the Actionable property and why AI fills missing context with its own assumptions (corpus §5.5).
}

::q3:: Which of the following specifications is the strongest example of the "bounded" property? {
~Explain machine learning in a way that is clear, concise, easy to follow, and fully appropriate for the background and knowledge level of the person who will be reading it#No — "clear," "concise," and "appropriate" describe desired qualities without setting any concrete limits on length, topic scope, audience, or what to exclude.
~Explain machine learning in enough detail for a general reader, touching on the key points and leaving out anything too advanced or likely to confuse someone who is new to the topic#No — "enough detail," "key points," and "too advanced" are unmeasurable; none of them tell the AI exactly where the fence around the task is drawn.
~Explain what machine learning is, covering the main ideas thoroughly, keeping the language accessible, and making sure the explanation is not too long or too technical#No — "main ideas," "not too long," and "not too technical" are vague; the AI has no concrete numbers, scope boundaries, or exclusion rules to work from.
=Explain supervised learning in plain English for someone who has never studied computers, in under 150 words, covering only what it is and one real-world example — do not include unsupervised learning, reinforcement learning, or any mathematical formulas#Correct — this sets explicit limits on length, audience level, topic scope, and named exclusions, which is exactly what bounded means.
#### Tests the Bounded property — explicit scope, length, audience, and exclusion limits (corpus §5.3).
}

::q4:: Which statement best explains the difference between the "observable" and "testable" properties? {
~Observable means the AI physically produced and saved a file you can open; testable means you felt satisfied with what you read once you reviewed the final output#No — satisfaction is subjective, not a fixed standard. Testable means you can check the output against a clear, objective pass/fail criterion that exists independently of how you feel.
=A result can be visible — you can see the AI produced something — yet still not testable if there is no clear standard to judge whether what it produced is actually correct#Correct — observable means the output is concrete and inspectable; testable means a clear pass/fail criterion exists. A result can satisfy one property without satisfying the other.
~Both mean the same thing — any output you can read or see can automatically be evaluated to determine whether it is correct or not#No — they are distinct. You can receive a summary you can read (observable) while still having no fixed standard to judge whether it captured the right information (not testable).
~Observable means the output is short enough to review in a few minutes; testable means it is detailed enough to evaluate thoroughly against your original goals#No — length has nothing to do with either property. Observable is about concreteness of the output; testable is about having a checkable standard to measure it against.
#### Tests the distinction between Observable and Testable — two related but separate properties that are both required (corpus §5.4).
}

::q5:: A colleague hands you the specification "Edit the report." You want to rewrite it so it passes all four properties. Which rewritten version best applies testable, bounded, observable, and actionable together? {
=Shorten the executive summary on page 1 to under 80 words, remove all jargon from section 2, correct all grammar errors in section 3, and return the edited document — do not alter any data or conclusions#Correct — each change is checkable against a clear criterion (testable), the scope is limited to three named sections (bounded), the output is a revised document you can inspect (observable), and every detail needed to start is present (actionable).
~Fix every grammar and tone problem throughout the entire report so it reads more professionally, sounds better to the intended audience, and is ready to send to the client when you are done#Not sufficient — "sounds better" cannot be checked against a clear criterion (not testable), no section limits are set (not fully bounded), and "intended audience" is still unnamed.
~Edit the report to improve its overall quality — focus on clarity and flow, keep it at a reasonable length, and make sure the writing style suits the audience and the purpose it was written for#Not sufficient — "improve," "reasonable length," and "suits the audience" are all unmeasurable; the AI has no concrete criteria, format rules, or scope limits to determine when it has finished correctly.
~Rewrite the entire report clearly for the senior leadership team using professional language, formal tone, and correct grammar throughout every section, then return it once all changes have been applied#Not sufficient — no measurable success criterion is defined so the AI cannot verify it is done (not testable), every section is in scope with no limits, and "professional language" remains a vague quality descriptor.
#### Tests rewriting a weak specification by applying all four properties together to a concrete real-world example (corpus §5.6, §6).
}

::q6:: A learner writes a specification for an AI task and then runs the four-property checklist. The output will be a concrete document they can read (observable ✓), the scope is limited to two named sections (bounded ✓), and every detail needed to start is present (actionable ✓). When they ask "Can I check the output against a clear standard?", they cannot answer yes. What should the learner do next? {
~Send the specification as-is, since three of the four checklist properties are already satisfied and one minor gap is acceptable when the task is clear#No — the checklist is a four-property gate; a specification that fails even one property will produce unreliable results, regardless of how many the others pass.
~Mark the observable checkbox as unchecked instead, since a result that cannot be checked against a clear standard is the same as a result that cannot be seen#No — observable and testable are separate properties; the learner confirmed the output is concrete and inspectable, so observable is satisfied. The missing property is testable.
=Revise the specification before sending it by adding measurable success criteria — such as a word count, a required number of items, or specific content that must appear — so the output can be checked against a fixed standard#Correct — a specification that cannot answer "Can I check the output against a clear standard?" is missing the testable property; the fix is to add explicit, measurable criteria before sending (corpus §6).
~Replace the specification with a shorter, simpler version — if a specification is hard to test, it usually contains too much detail, and removing constraints will make it easier to evaluate#No — removing constraints makes a specification weaker, not more testable. Testability requires adding measurable criteria, not stripping existing bounds away.
#### Tests the ability to self-evaluate a written specification against the four-property checklist and identify the correct fix when one property fails (corpus §6, §9).
}
